snippet.textDisplay: Coconut milk was first found for purchase in a Hispanic Mexican Store; later found in an Indian store and finally purchased while shopping in Whole Foods Market. Later purchases were in a box instead of a can. I started looking for pull top vs can requiring a can opener. The recipe has always been for a rice but then I found sweetened coconut milk taste good with dry cereal. Next, Yes, I read good for those lactose intolerant. Many years later, just concentrated on coconut milk for a recipe and I need kitchen tools and ramekins.

snippet.textDisplay:
I imagine that someone in the previous 3070 comments may have pointed this out already, but on the off chance no one has, the reason you bring it to a simmer is most likely to activate the thickening power of the arrowroot flour (in addition to softening the cashews as you pointed out), which could be why yours was so runny. The recipe says 1 minute once simmering, not 1 minute total, so it needed to get hotter for the right chemical reactions to take place.



But runny or not it clearly came out very delicious, and I'm excited you did it because my mum loves this dish and my sister is vegan so we're always on the lookout for tasty desserts we can make on special occasions that everyone can eat.
snippet.textOriginal:
I imagine that someone in the previous 3070 comments may have pointed this out already, but on the off chance no one has, the reason you bring it to a simmer is most likely to activate the thickening power of the arrowroot flour (in addition to softening the cashews as you pointed out), which could be why yours was so runny. The recipe says 1 minute once simmering, not 1 minute total, so it needed to get hotter for the right chemical reactions to take place. 



But runny or not it clearly came out very delicious, and I'm excited you did it because my mum loves this dish and my sister is vegan so we're always on the lookout for tasty desserts we can make on special occasions that everyone can eat.
